Taiwan Stocks: China Airlines, Formosa Chemicals, Oriental Union

-- B y   W e i y i   L i m
-- 
2011-06-30T06:01:09Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-06-30/formosa-chemicals-fibre-promos-wintek-taiwan-stocks-preview.html
Shares of the following companies
had unusual moves in  Taiwan  trading. Stock symbols are in
parentheses and prices are as of 1:30 p.m. in Taipei.  The Taiex Index rose 79.21 points, or 0.9 percent, to
8,652.59, the highest close since June 16. The benchmark gauge
fell 3.7 percent in June, the most since February, and declined
0.4 percent this quarter, the second straight loss.  China Airlines Ltd. (2610)  (2610 TT), Taiwan’s largest carrier,
retreated 1.5 percent to NT$19.50.  EVA Airways Corp. (2618)  (2618 TT)
fell 0.2 percent to NT$29.30. Crude gained for a third day,
extending the biggest two-day rally in seven weeks.  Formosa Chemicals & Fibre Corp. (1326)  (1326 TT) dropped 0.5
percent to NT$107. The petrochemical maker was cut to “sell”
from “hold” at Citigroup Inc., which said earnings peaked in
the first quarter. The brokerage said it favors a switch to
 Oriental Union Chemical Corp. (1710)  (1710 TT) or  Formosa Plastics
Corp. (1301)  (1301 TT). Oriental Union gained 1.5 percent to NT$42.
Formosa Plastics increased 3.5 percent to NT$103.50.  ProMOS Technologies Inc. (5387)  (5387 TT) surged 6 percent to
NT$0.71 after the Commercial Times reported banks have agreed to
cut the loan rates they charge ProMOS to 0.1 percent from 3.5
percent, without saying where it got the information. Ben Tseng,
spokesman for the company, declined to comment when contacted on
his mobile phone.  To contact the reporter on this story:
Weiyi Lim in Singapore at 
 wlim26@bloomberg.net   To contact the editor responsible for this story:
